-body-2675998490" data-headline=3D"Lab-On-a-Chip Grippers Could Handle Huma=
n Cells"><div class=3D"body-description"><p><a href=3D"https://spectrum.iee=
e.org/tag/living-cells" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked" target=3D"_blank">Living=
 cells</a> and tissues grown in the lab are vital tools for helping scienti=
sts learn about basic biology and test new drugs. Growing miniature organs =
on a chip from a person=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/=
stem-cells" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked" target=3D"_blank">stem cells</a> cou=
ld even one day help doctors test <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/the-=
ultimate-in-personalized-medicine-your-body-on-a-chip" target=3D"_blank" cl=
ass=3D"rm-stats-tracked">personalized treatments</a>. </p><p>Now, researche=
rs have developed a <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/lab-on-chip" c=
lass=3D"rm-stats-tracked" target=3D"_blank">lab-on-chip</a> that adds a new=
 feature to these systems: <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/low-pow=
er" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked" target=3D"_blank">low-power</a> <a href=3D"h=
ttps://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/grippers" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked" target=3D=
"_blank">grippers</a> that can hold cells or tiny organ models called organ=
oids in place. The CMOS-compatible <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag=
/lab-on-a-chip" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked" target=3D"_blank">lab-on-a-chip<=
/a> features shape-memory grippers and <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org=
/tag/chemical-sensors" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked" target=3D"_blank">chemica=
l sensors</a> for detecting molecules such as <a href=3D"https://spectrum.i=
eee.org/tag/neurotransmitters" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked" target=3D"_blank"=
>neurotransmitters</a>. The micro-cage array was <a href=3D"https://submiss=
ions.mirasmart.com/ISSCC2026/Itinerary/PresentationDetail.aspx?evdid=3D126"=
 rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked">p=
resented</a> in San Francisco on 18 February at the IEEE International Soli=
d State Circuits Conference.</p><p>Researchers working on this multifunctio=
nal system hope it will be used to sense and manipulate biological samples =
of different sizes and potentially help direct the development of stem cell=
s into organoids, which are used to study basic biology and drugs. Growing =
<a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/organoid-intelligence-computing-on-bra=
in" target=3D"_blank" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked">neural organoids</a> in la=
b-on-a-chip systems, for instance, can help biologists study brain developm=
ent and how it=E2=80=99s impacted by chemicals or drugs. Cage-like grippers=
 could be used to hold samples in place, or to bring tissue samples next to=
 each other to encourage their development.</p><p>Building bioelectronic sy=
stems directly on a chip is attractive because it makes it easy to integrat=
e many different features, including chemical sensing, electrical sensing a=
nd stimulation, and physical manipulation. However, manipulating biological=
 samples on <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/cmos" class=3D"rm-stat=
s-tracked" target=3D"_blank">CMOS</a> chips can be tricky, says <a href=3D"=
https://ee.ethz.ch/the-department/people-a-z/person-detail.MzExMDIy.TGlzdC8=
zMjc5LC0xNjUwNTg5ODIw.html" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank" c=
lass=3D"rm-stats-tracked">Adam Wang</a>, an electrical engineer at <a href=
=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/eth-zurich" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked" ta=
rget=3D"_blank">ETH Zurich</a>. Optical and acoustic tweezers, for example,=
 can heat up, while the <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/electric-f=
ields" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked" target=3D"_blank">electric fields</a> use=
d to generate motion in <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/bio=
chemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology/dielectrophoresis" target=3D"_blan=
k" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked">dieletrophoresis</a> can be weakened by high =
concentrations of ions in the media used to support cells and tissues. Thes=
e methods also require continuous power inputs. Wang presented the research=
 on behalf of lead student <a href=3D"https://ee.ethz.ch/the-department/peo=
ple-a-z/person-detail.MjY1NDY3.TGlzdC8zMjc5LC0xNjUwNTg5ODIw.html" rel=3D"no=
opener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked">Zhikai Huan=
g</a>, who was unable to attend.<strong></strong></p><p></p><div class=3D"r=
blad-ieee_in_content"><div class=3D"rbl-ad" id=3D"rblad-3" data-unit=3D"IEE=
