        col1" id=3D"rebelltitem1" data-id=3D"1" data-reload-ads=3D"false" d=
ata-is-image=3D"False" data-href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/digital-surve=
illance/particle-1" data-basename=3D"particle-1" data-post-id=3D"2676085233=
" data-published-at=3D"1773258802" data-use-pagination=3D"False">
        <p><strong>Computer-Generated Voice: </strong>Attention, a crash ha=
s occurred. Line open.</p><p><strong>911 Operator: </strong>Hello. Can anyo=
ne hear me?</p><p><strong>Unidentified Woman:</strong> Yes, yes.</p><p><str=
ong>911 Operator:</strong> Okay. This is 911. You=E2=80=99ve been involved =
in an accident.</p><p><strong>Unidentified Woman:</strong> No.</p><p><stron=
g>911 Operator:</strong> Well, your car called in to us because it said you=
=E2=80=99d been involved in an accident. Are you sure everything=E2=80=99s =
okay?</p><p><strong>Unidentified Woman:</strong> Everything=E2=80=99s okay.=
</p><p><strong>911 Operator:</strong> Okay. Are you broke down?</p><p><stro=
ng>Unidentified Woman:</strong> No, I=E2=80=99m fine. The guy that hit me=
=E2=80=94he did not turn.</p><p><strong>911 Operator:</strong> Okay, so you=
 have been involved in an accident.</p><p><strong>Unidentified Woman: </str=
ong>No, I haven=E2=80=99t.</p><p><strong>911 Operator:</strong> Did you hit=
 a car?</p><p><strong>Unidentified Woman:</strong> No, I didn=E2=80=99t.</p=
><p><strong>911 Operator: </strong>Did you leave the scene of an accident?<=
/p><p><strong>Unidentified Woman: </strong>No. I would never do anything li=
ke that.</p>
</div><p></p><p><span>Apparently, Bernstein did do something =E2=80=9Clike =
that.=E2=80=9D She was soon caught and cited for leaving the scene of the a=
ccident. Her own car provided evidence of her guilt.</span></p><h2>The Rise=
 of =E2=80=9CSensorveillance=E2=80=9D</h2><p>Once upon a time, our things w=
ere just things. A bike was a tool for biking. It got you from one location=
 to another, but it didn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cknow=E2=80=9D more about your t=
ravels than any other inanimate object did. It was dumb in a comforting way=
, and we used it as intended. Today, a top-of-the-line bike can track your =
route and calculate your average speed along the way. Hop on an <a href=3D"=
https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/e-bike">e-bike</a> from a commercial bike sha=
re, and it will collect data for your trip, plus the trips of everyone else=
 who used it that month.</p><p>These =E2=80=9Csmart=E2=80=9D objects belong=
 to what technologist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_Ashton=
" target=3D"_blank">Kevin Ashton</a> named the <a href=3D"https://spectrum.=
ieee.org/tag/internet-of-things" target=3D"_self">Internet of Things</a>. A=
shton proposed adding radio-frequency identification (<a href=3D"https://sp=
ectrum.ieee.org/tag/rfid" target=3D"_self">RFID</a>) tags and sensors to ev=
eryday objects, allowing them to collect data that could be fed into networ=
ked systems without human intervention. A sensor in a river could monitor t=
he cleanliness of the water. A tag on a bottle of shampoo could trace its j=
ourney throughout the <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/supply-chain=
">supply chain</a>. Add enough sensors to enough objects and you can model =
the health of an entire ecosystem=E2=80=94or learn whether you=E2=80=99re s=
ending too much of your inventory to Massachusetts and too little to Texas.=
</p><p>Ashton first theorized the Internet of Things (<a href=3D"https://sp=
ectrum.ieee.org/tag/iot">IoT</a>) in the late 1990s. Today, the IoT goes we=
ll beyond his initial vision, including not only RFID tags but also sensors=
 with <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/wi-fi">Wi-Fi</a>, <a href=3D=
"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/bluetooth">Bluetooth</a>, cellular, and <a h=
ref=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/gps">GPS</a> connections. These small,=
 low-cost sensors record data about movement, heat, pressure, or location a=
nd can engage in two-way communication.</p><p>Of course, such a system is a=
lso, by necessity, a system of surveillance. =E2=80=9CSensorveillance=E2=80=
=9D=E2=80=94a term I created to highlight the intersection of sensors and s=
urveillance=E2=80=94is slowly becoming the default across the developed wor=
ld.</p><h2>Cellphone Surveillance Networks</h2><p>Let=E2=80=99s start with =
phones. You=E2=80=99re probably not surprised that your cellphone company t=
racks your location; that=E2=80=99s how cellphones work. Both <a href=3D"ht=
tps://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/smartphones">smartphones</a> and =E2=80=9Cdumb=
=E2=80=9D mobile phones use local cell towers, owned by cellphone companies=
, to connect you to your friends and family, which means those companies kn=
ow which towers you are near at all times.</p><p>If you always carry your p=
hone with you, your phone=E2=80=99s whereabouts=E2=80=94recorded as cell-si=
te location information (<a href=3D"https://www.defendyouthrights.org/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2017/10/Cell-Phone-Location-Tracking-or-CSLI-A-Guide-for-Crim=
inal-Defense-Attorneys.pdf" target=3D"_blank">CSLI</a>)=E2=80=94reveal your=
s. One man, Timothy Carpenter, found this out the hard way after he and a g=
roup of associates set out to rob a series of electronics stores. Carpenter=
 was the alleged ringleader, but he didn=E2=80=99t enter the stores himself=
. He served as the lookout, waiting in the car while his associates stuffed=
 merchandise into bags.</p><p>It might have been hard for investigators to =
tie him to the crimes=E2=80=94if not for the fact that every minute he kept=
 watch, his cellphone was pinging a local tower, logging his location. Usin=
g that information, the <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/fbi">FBI</=
a> was able to determine that he had been near each store during the exact =
moment of each robbery.</p><p>Cell signals are the tip of the proverbial da=
ta iceberg. If you have a smartphone, you=E2=80=99re almost certainly using=
 something created by <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/google">Goog=
le</a>. Google makes money off advertising. The more Google knows about use=
rs, the better it can target ads to them. Google=E2=80=99s location service=
s are on all <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/android">Android</a> =
phones, which use the company=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.or=
g/tag/operating-system">operating system</a>, but they=E2=80=99re also on G=
oogle apps, including <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/google-maps"=
>Google Maps</a> and <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/gmail">Gmail<=
/a>.</p><p>For years, all that location information ended up in what the co=
mpany called <a href=3D"https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2019/04/googles-senso=
rvault-can-tell-police-where-youve-been" target=3D"_blank">the Sensorvault<=
/a>. The Sensorvault, as the name suggests, combined data from GPS, Bluetoo=
th, cell towers, IP addresses, and Wi-Fi signals to create a powerful <a hr=
ef=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/tracking-system">tracking system</a> th=
at could identify a phone=E2=80=99s location with great precision. As you m=
ight imagine, police saw it as a digital evidence miracle. In 2020, Google =
received more than 11,500 warrants from law enforcement seeking information=
 from the Sensorvault.</p><p class=3D"pull-quote">=E2=80=9CSensorveillance=
=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94a term I created to highlight the intersection of sensors=
 and surveillance=E2=80=94is slowly becoming the default across the develop=
ed world.</p><p>In 2024, Google announced that it would <a href=3D"https://=
www.forbes.com/sites/larsdaniel/2024/10/08/google-to-stop-sharing-location-=
data-with-law-enforcement/" target=3D"_blank">no longer retain all of this =
data in the cloud</a>. Instead, the geolocation information would be stored=
 on individual devices, requiring police to get a warrant for a specific de=
vice. The demise of the Sensorvault came about through a change in corporat=
e policy, which could be reversed. But at least for now, Google has made it=
 significantly harder for police to access its data.</p><p>And while the Se=
nsorvault was the biggest source of geolocational evidence, it is far from =
the only one. Even apps that have nothing to do with maps or navigation mig=
ht nonetheless be collecting your location data. In one Pennsylvania case, =
prosecutors learned that a burglar used an <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee=
.org/tag/iphone">iPhone</a> flashlight app to search through a home, and th=
ey used the data from the app to prove he was in the home at the time of th=
e break-in. These apps might be advertised as =E2=80=9Cfree,=E2=80=9D but t=
hey come with a hidden cost.</p><p>Cars, increasingly, <a href=3D"https://w=
ww.mozillafoundation.org/en/blog/privacy-nightmare-on-wheels-every-car-bran=
d-reviewed-by-mozilla-including-ford-volkswagen-and-toyota-flunks-privacy-t=
est/" target=3D"_blank">collect almost as much information</a> as phones. M=
obile extraction devices can collect <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/t=
ag/digital-forensics">digital forensics</a> about a car=E2=80=99s speed, wh=
en its airbags deployed, when its brakes were engaged, and where it was whe=
n all that happened. If you connect your phone to play <a href=3D"https://s=
pectrum.ieee.org/tag/spotify">Spotify</a> or to read out your texts, then y=
our call logs, contact lists, <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/soci=
al-media">social media</a> accounts, and entertainment selections can be do=
wnloaded directly from your vehicle. Because cars are involved in so many c=
rimes (either as the instrument of the crime or as transportation), searche=
s of this data are becoming more commonplace.</p><p>Even without physically=
 extracting information from the car, police have other ways to get the dat=
a. After all, the car=E2=80=99s built-in <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.o=
rg/tag/telemetry">telemetry</a> system is sharing information with third pa=
rties. In addition to the usual personal information you give up when buyin=
g a car (name, address, phone number, email, Social Security number, driver=
=E2=80=99s license number), when you own a Stellantis-brand car, the compan=
y collects how often you use the car, your speed, and instances of accelera=
tion or braking. <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/nissan">Nissan</a=
> asserts the right to collect information about =E2=80=9Csexual activity, =
health diagnosis data, and genetic [data]=E2=80=9D in addition to =E2=80=9C=
preferences, characteristics, psychological trends, predispositions, behavi=
or, attitudes, intelligence, abilities, and aptitudes.=E2=80=9D Nissan=E2=
=80=99s privacy policy specifically reserves the right to provide this info=
rmation to both data brokers and law enforcement.</p><h2>The Law of Smart T=
hings</h2><p>The fact that government agents can glean so much information =
from our things does not mean that they should be able to do so at any time=
 or for any reason. The <a href=3D"https://constitution.congress.gov/consti=
tution/amendment-4/" target=3D"_blank">U.S. Fourth Amendment</a>=E2=80=94dr=
afted in an era without electricity=E2=80=94protects =E2=80=9Cpersons, hous=
es, papers, and effects=E2=80=9D against unreasonable search and seizure, b=
ut is naturally silent on the question of location data.</p><p>The first qu=
estion is whether the data from our smart things should be constitutionally=
 protected from police. In the language of the constitutional text, the sma=
rt device itself is an =E2=80=9Ceffect=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94a movable piece of =
personal property. But what about the data collected by the effect? Is the =
location data collected by your smartwatch considered part of the watch, or=
 part of the person wearing the watch? Neither? Both?</p><p>To its credit, =
the U.S. Supreme Court has addressed some of the hard questions around digi=
tal tracking. In two cases, the first involving GPS tracking of a car and t=
he second involving the CSLI tracking of Timothy Carpenter=E2=80=99s cellph=
one, the court has placed limits on the government=E2=80=99s ability to col=
lect location data over the long term.</p><p><a href=3D"https://www.oyez.or=
g/cases/2011/10-1259" target=3D"_blank"><em><em>United States v. Jones</em>=
</em></a> involved GPS tracking of a car. Antoine Jones owned a nightclub i=
n Washington, D.C. He also sold cocaine and found himself under criminal in=
vestigation for a large-scale drug distribution scheme. To prove Jones=E2=
=80=99s connection to =E2=80=9Cthe stash house,=E2=80=9D police placed a GP=
S device on his wife=E2=80=99s Jeep Cherokee. This was before GPS came stan=
dard in cars, so the device was physically attached to the undercarriage of=
 the vehicle.</p><p>Data about Jones=E2=80=99s travels was recorded for 28 =
days, during which he visited the stash house multiple times. The prosecuto=
rs introduced the GPS data at trial, and Jones was found guilty. Jones appe=
aled his conviction, arguing that the warrantless use of a GPS device to tr=
ack his car violated his <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/fourth-am=
endment">Fourth Amendment</a> rights.</p><p class=3D"pull-quote">=E2=80=9CW=
hen the Government tracks the location of a cell phone it achieves near per=
fect surveillance.=E2=80=9D <strong>=E2=80=94 the Supreme Court</strong></p=
><p>In 2012, the Supreme Court held that a warrant was required, based on t=
he reasoning that the physical placement of the GPS device on the Jeep was =
itself a Fourth Amendment search requiring a warrant. Justice Sonia Sotomay=
or agreed regarding the physical search but went further, discussing the ha=
rms of long-term GPS tracking: =E2=80=9CGPS monitoring generates a precise,=
 comprehensive record of a person=E2=80=99s public movements that reflects =
a wealth of detail about her familial, political, professional, religious, =
and sexual associations.=E2=80=9D</p><p>Timothy Carpenter=E2=80=99s ill-fat=
ed robbery spree gave the Supreme Court another chance to address the const=
itutional harms of long-term tracking. In their attempts to connect Carpent=
er to the six electronics stores that had been robbed, federal investigator=
s requested 127 days of location data from two mobile phone carriers. The p=
roblem for the police, however, was that they had obtained the information =
on Carpenter without a judicial warrant.</p><p>Carpenter challenged the FBI=
=E2=80=99s acquisition of his CSLI, claiming that it violated his reasonabl=
e expectation of privacy. In <a href=3D"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2017/16-=
402" target=3D"_blank">a 5=E2=80=934 opinion</a>, the Supreme Court determi=
ned that the acquisition of long-term CSLI was a Fourth Amendment search, w=
hich required a warrant. As the Court stated in its 2018 ruling: =E2=80=9CA=
 cell phone faithfully follows its owner beyond public thoroughfares and in=
to private residences, doctor=E2=80=99s offices, political headquarters, an=
d other potentially revealing locales.... [W]hen the Government tracks the =
location of a cell phone it achieves near perfect surveillance.=E2=80=9D</p=
><p><em><em>Jones</em></em> and <em><em>Carpenter</em></em> are helpful for=
 setting the boundaries of location-based searches. But, in truth, the case=
s generate a lot more questions than answers. What about surveillance that =
is not long-term? At what point does the aggregation of details about a per=
son=E2=80=99s location violate their reasonable expectation of privacy?</p>=
<h2>The Warrant According to Google</h2><p>Okelle Chatrie=E2=80=99s case, i=
n which police used Google=E2=80=99s location data to identify him as the m=
ystery bank robber, offers a stark warning about the limits of Fourth Amend=
ment protections under these circumstances. It=E2=80=99s also a terrific ex=
ample of why <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/capitol-riot" target=3D"_=
self">=E2=80=9Cgeofence=E2=80=9D warrants</a>, which request information wi=
thin a certain geographic boundary, are appealing to police. From surveilla=
nce footage, detectives could see that the suspect had a phone to his ear w=
hen he walked into the bank. A geofence could identify who the suspect was,=
 and likely where he came from and where he went. Google held the answer in=
 its virtual vault. A warrant gave investigators the key.</p><p>The police =
cast a broad net. The geofence warrant asked for data on all the cellphones=
 within a 150-meter radius, an area, as the court described it, =E2=80=9Cab=
out three and a half times the footprint of a New York city block.=E2=80=9D=
 After receiving the police=E2=80=99s initial request for information on al=
l the phones in the area, Google returned 19 anonymized numbers. Over the c=
ourse of a three-step warrant process, the company narrowed those 19 phones=
 down to three and then to one, which it revealed as belonging to Okelle Ch=
atrie.</p><p class=3D"pull-quote">If the police wish to buy the data, just =
like an insurer or marketing firm might, how can you object? It=E2=80=99s n=
ot your data.</p><p>The three-step warrant process is a unique innovation i=
n the digital evidence space. Google=E2=80=99s lawyers developed a procedur=
e whereby detectives seeking targeted geolocation data had to file three se=
parate requests, first requesting identifying numbers in an area, then narr=
owing the request based on other information, and finally obtaining an orde=
r to unmask the anonymous number (or numbers) by providing a name.</p><p>To=
 be clear, Google=E2=80=94a private company=E2=80=94required the government=
 to jump through these hoops because Google considered it important to prot=
ect its customers=E2=80=99 data. It was the company=E2=80=99s lawyers=E2=80=
=94not the courts or the government=E2=80=94who demanded these warrants.</p=
><h2>Buying Data</h2><p>Warrants provide at least some procedural barrier t=
o <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/data-collection">data collection=
</a> by police. If government agencies want to avoid that minor hassle, the=
y can simply buy the data instead. By contracting with data-location servic=
es, several federal agencies have already done so.</p><p>The logic for this=
 Fourth Amendment loophole is straightforward: You gave your data to a thir=
d-party company, and the company can use it as it wishes. If you own a car =
that is smart enough to collect driving analytics, you clicked some agreeme=
nt saying the car company could use the data=E2=80=94study it, analyze it, =
and, if it wants, sell it. If you don=E2=80=99t want to give them data in t=
he first place, that is okay (although it will likely result in less optima=
l functionality), but you cannot rightly complain when they use the data yo=
u gave them in ways that benefit them. If the police wish to buy the data, =
just like an insurer or marketing firm might, how can you object? It=E2=80=
=99s not your data.</p><h2>Who Is to Blame?</h2><p>Fears about the amount o=
f personal information that could be revealed with long-term GPS surveillan=
ce have become reality. Today, police don=E2=80=99t need to plant a device =
to track your movements=E2=80=94they can rely on your car or phone to do it=
 for them.</p><p>This happened because companies sold convenience and consu=
mers bought it. So it might be tempting to blame ourselves. We=E2=80=99re t=
he ones buying this technology. If we don=E2=80=99t want to be tracked, we =
can always go back to using paper maps and writing down directions by hand.=
 If few of us are willing to make that trade, that=E2=80=99s on us.</p><p>B=
ut it=E2=80=99s not that easy. You may still be able to choose a dumb bike =
over a smart one, but a car that tracks you will soon be the only type of c=
ar you can buy. And while cars and data can, in theory, be separated, that=
=E2=80=99s not true for all our smart things. Without cell-signal tracking =
capabilities, a cellphone is just a paperweight. And in today=E2=80=99s wor=
ld, living without a phone or a car is simply not practical for many people=
.</p><p>There are technological steps we can take toward protecting privacy=
. Companies can localize the data the sensors generate within the devices t=
hemselves, rather than in a central location like the Sensorvault. Similarl=
y, the information that allows you to unlock your Apple iPhone via <a href=
=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/facial-recognition" target=3D"_self">faci=
al recognition</a> stays localized on the phone. These are technological fi=
xes, and positive ones. But even localized data is available to police with=
 a warrant.</p><p>This is the puzzle of the digital age. We can=E2=80=99t=
=E2=80=94or don=E2=80=99t want to=E2=80=94avoid creating data, but that dat=
a, once created, becomes available for legal ends. The power to track every=
 person is the perfect tool for authoritarianism. For every wondrous story =
about catching a criminal, there will be a terrifying story of tracking a p=
olitical enemy or suppressing dissent. Such immense power can and will be a=
bused. <span class=3D"ieee-end-mark"></span></p><div class=3D"post-pager js=
