ate-url css-listicle-body-2676089558" data-headline=3D"New Polymer Blend Co=
uld Help Store Energy for the Grid and EVs" data-elid=3D"2676089558" data-p=
ost-url=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/polymer-blend-capacitor" data-authors=
=3D"Catherine Arnold" data-page-title=3D"Polymer Blend Capacitor Packs Four=
 Times More Energy - IEEE Spectrum"><div class=3D"body-description"><div cl=
ass=3D"widget__brief"><p>As electronics demand higher <a href=3D"https://sp=
ectrum.ieee.org/tag/energy-density" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked" target=3D"_b=
lank">energy density</a>, one component has proved challenging to shrink: t=
he capacitor. Making a smaller capacitor usually requires thinning the <a h=
ref=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/dielectric" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked"=
 target=3D"_blank">dielectric</a> layer or electrode surface area, which ha=
s often resulted in a reduction of power. A new polymer material could help=
 change that.</p><p>In a study published 18 February in <em>Nature</em>, a =
Pennsylvania State University-led team <a href=3D"https://www.nature.com/ar=
ticles/s41586-026-10195-2" target=3D"_blank" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked">rep=
orted a capacitor</a> crafted from a polymer blend that can operate at temp=
eratures up to 250 =C2=B0C while storing roughly four times as much energy =
as conventional polymer <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/capacitors=
" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked" target=3D"_blank">capacitors</a>. Today=E2=80=
=99s advanced polymer capacitors typically function only up to about 100 =
=C2=B0C, meaning engineers often rely on bulky cooling systems in high-powe=
r electronics. The research team has filed a patent for the polymer capacit=
ors and plans to bring them to market.</p></div>
            <div class=3D"content-container"></div>
            <div class=3D"js-appear-on-expand">
                <template><p>Capacitors deliver rapid bursts of energy and =
stabilize voltage in circuits, making them essential in applications rangin=
g from <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/electric-vehicles">electric=
 vehicles</a> and aerospace electronics to power-grid infrastructure and AI=
 <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/data-centers">data centers</a>. Y=
et while <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/transistor-density" target=3D=
"_blank">transistors have steadily shrunk</a> with advances in <a href=3D"h=
ttps://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/semiconductor-manufacturing">semiconductor man=
ufacturing</a>, <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/passive-components=
">passive components</a> such as capacitors and <a href=3D"https://spectrum=
.ieee.org/tag/inductors">inductors</a> have not scaled at the same pace.</p=
><p>=E2=80=9CCapacitors can account for 30 to 40 percent of the volume in s=
ome <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/power-electronics">power elect=
ronics</a> systems,=E2=80=9D says <a href=3D"https://www.matse.psu.edu/dire=
ctory/qiming-zhang" target=3D"_blank">Qiming Zhang</a>, an <a href=3D"https=
://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/electrical-engineering">electrical engineering</a>=
 researcher at <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/penn-state">Penn St=
ate</a> and study author, explaining why it=E2=80=99s important to make sma=
ller capacitors.</p><h2>A plastics blend more powerful than its parts</h2><=
p>The research team combined two commercially available engineered plastics=
: polyetherimide (PEI), originally developed by <a href=3D"https://spectrum=
.ieee.org/tag/general-electric">General Electric</a> and widely used in ind=
ustrial equipment, and PBPDA, known for strong heat resistance and electric=
al insulation. <span>When processed together under controlled conditions, t=
he <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/polymers">polymers</a> self-ass=
emble into nanoscale structures that form thin dielectric films inside capa=
citors. Those structures help suppress electrical leakage while allowing th=
e material to polarize strongly in an <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/=
tag/electric-field">electric field</a>, allowing greater <a href=3D"https:/=
/spectrum.ieee.org/tag/energy-storage">energy storage</a>.</span></p><p></p=
><div class=3D"rblad-ieee_in_content"></div><p></p><p>The resulting materia=
l exhibits an unusually <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/high-k-die=
lectric" target=3D"_blank">high dielectric constant</a>=E2=80=94a measure o=
f how much electrical energy a material can store. Most polymer dielectrics=
 have values around four, but the blended polymer dielectric in the new wor=
k had a value of 13.5.</p><p>=E2=80=9CIf you look at the literature up to n=
ow, no one has reached this level of dielectric constant in this type of po=
lymer system,=E2=80=9D Zhang says. =E2=80=9CPutting two commonly used polym=
ers together and seeing this kind of performance was a surprise to many peo=
ple.=E2=80=9D</p><p>Because the material can remain operational even at ele=
vated temperatures=E2=80=94such as <strong></strong>those from extreme envi=
ronmental heat or <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/hot-chips" target=3D=
"_blank">hot spots</a> in densely built components=E2=80=94capacitors built=
 from this polymer could potentially store the same amount of energy in a s=
maller package.<strong> </strong></p><p>=E2=80=9CWith this material, you ca=
n make the same device using about [one-fourth as much] material,=E2=80=9D =
Zhang says. =E2=80=9CBecause the polymers themselves are inexpensive, the c=
ost does not increase. At the same time, the component can become smaller a=
nd lighter.=E2=80=9D</p><h2>How the polymer mix improves capacitors</h2><p>=
The researchers=E2=80=99 finding is =E2=80=9Ca big advancement,=E2=80=9D sa=
ys <a href=3D"https://www.chee.uh.edu/faculty/karim" target=3D"_blank">Alam=
gir Karim</a>, a polymer research director at the University of Houston who=
 was not involved in the Penn State development. =E2=80=9CNormally when you=
 mix polymers, you don=E2=80=99t expect the dielectric constant to increase=
.=E2=80=9D</p><p>Karim says the effect likely arises from nanoscale interfa=
ces created when the polymers partially separate. <span>=E2=80=9CAt about a=
 50=E2=80=9350 mixture, the polymers don=E2=80=99t fully mix and instead cr=
eate a very large interfacial area,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=80=9CThose interf=
aces may be where the unusual electrical behavior comes from.=E2=80=9D</spa=
n></p><p>If the material can be produced at scale, it could help address a =
key bottleneck in high-power electronics. Higher-temperature capacitors cou=
ld reduce cooling requirements and allow engineers to pack more power into =
smaller systems=E2=80=94an advantage for aerospace platforms, electric vehi=
cles, the <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/electric-grid">electric =
grid</a>, and other high-temperature environments.</p><p>But translating th=
e concept from laboratory methods to commercial manufacturing may present c=
hallenges, says <a href=3D"https://www.linkedin.com/in/zongliang-xie-255b3b=
27a/" target=3D"_blank">Zongliang Xie</a>, a postdoctoral researcher at the=
 <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/lawrence-berkeley-national-labora=
tory">Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory</a>. <span>The Penn State team =
is now </span><span>producing small dielectric films, but industrial capaci=
tor manufacturing typically requires continuous rolls of material that can =
extend for kilometers.</span></p><p>=E2=80=9CIndustry generally prefers ext=
rusion-based processing because it=E2=80=99s easier and cheaper to control,=
=E2=80=9D Xie says. =E2=80=9CScaling to produce great lengths of film while=
 maintaining the same structure and performance could complicate matters. T=
here=E2=80=99s potential, but it=E2=80=99s also challenging.=E2=80=9D</p><p=
>Still, researchers say the discovery demonstrates that new performance lim=
its may still be unlocked using familiar materials. <span>=E2=80=9CDevelopi=
ng the material is only the first step,=E2=80=9D Zhang says. =E2=80=9CBut i=
t shows people that this barrier can be broken.=E2=80=9D</span></p><p></p><=
