ss=3D"photo-caption">
        <p>The French company Theryq is collaborating with the particle phy=
sics research facility CERN to develop FLASH radiation therapy. Theryq's FL=
ASHKNiFE system targets superficial tumors with electron beams of 6 or 9 me=
gaelectron volts. </p>
    </div><div class=3D"photo-credit">
        THERYQ
    </div><div class=3D"body js-expandable clearfix js-listicle-body js-upd=
ate-url css-listicle-body-2675544839" data-headline=3D"The Millisecond That=
 Could Change Cancer Treatment" data-elid=3D"2675544839" data-post-url=3D"h=
ttps://spectrum.ieee.org/flash-radiotherapy" data-authors=3D"Tom Clynes" da=
ta-page-title=3D"FLASH Radiotherapy's Bold Approach to Cancer Treatment - I=
EEE Spectrum"><div class=3D"body-description"><div class=3D"widget__brief">=
<p><strong>Inside a cavernous hall</strong> at the Swiss-French border, the=
 air hums with high voltage and possibility. From his perch on the wraparou=
nd observation deck, physicist <a href=3D"https://www.researchgate.net/prof=
ile/Walter-Wuensch" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank" class=3D"=
rm-stats-tracked">Walter Wuensch</a> surveys a multimillion-dollar array of=
 accelerating cavities, klystrons, modulators, and pulse compressors=E2=80=
=94hardware being readied to drive a new generation of linear particle acce=
lerators.</p><p>Wuensch has spent decades working with these machines to cr=
ack the deepest mysteries of the universe. Now he and his colleagues are ai=
ming at a new target: cancer. Here at <a href=3D"https://home.cern/" rel=3D=
"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank" class=3D"rm-stats-tracked">CERN</a>=
 (the European Organization for Nuclear Research) and other particle-physic=
s labs, scientists and engineers are applying the tools of fundamental phys=
ics to develop a technique called FLASH radiotherapy that offers a radical =
and counterintuitive vision for treating the disease.</p></div>
            <div class=3D"content-container"></div>
            <div class=3D"js-appear-on-expand">
                <template><p class=3D"shortcode-media shortcode-media-rebel=
mouse-image rm-float-left rm-resized-container rm-resized-container-25" dat=
a-rm-resized-container=3D"25%" style=3D"float: left;">        <img id=3D"f8=
147" data-rm-shortcode-id=3D"ce95648ce39bd5c09f73bddf6af75766" data-rm-shor=
tcode-name=3D"rebelmouse-image" class=3D"rm-shortcode rm-lazyloadable-image=
 " lazy-loadable=3D"true" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http:=
//www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%202000%202667'%3E%3C/svg%3E" data=
-runner-src=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/media-library/photo-of-a-white-hai=
red-man-standing-next-to-floor-to-ceiling-experimental-equipment-with-many-=
tubes-and-wires.jpg?id=3D65111429&amp;width=3D980" width=3D"2000" height=3D=
"2667" alt=3D"Photo of a white-haired man standing next to floor-to-ceiling=
 experimental equipment with many tubes and wires. ">                      =
  <small class=3D"image-media media-caption" placeholder=3D"Add Photo Capti=
on...">CERN researcher Walter Wuensch says the particle physics lab=E2=80=
=99s work on FLASH radiotherapy is =E2=80=9Cgenerating a lot of excitement.=
=E2=80=9D</small><small class=3D"image-media media-photo-credit" placeholde=
r=3D"Add Photo Credit...">CERN</small></p><p>Radiation therapy has been a c=
ornerstone of cancer treatment since shortly after <a href=3D"https://medic=
almuseum.health.mil/index.cfm/visit/exhibits/virtual/xraydiscovery/index" t=
arget=3D"_blank">Wilhelm Conrad R=C3=B6ntgen</a> discovered X-rays in 1895.=
 Today, more than half of all cancer patients receive it as part of their c=
are, typically in relatively low doses of X-rays delivered over dozens of s=
essions. Although this approach often kills the tumor, it also wreaks havoc=
 on nearby healthy tissue. Even with modern precision targeting, the potent=
ial for collateral damage limits how much radiation doctors can safely deli=
ver.</p><p>FLASH radiotherapy flips the conventional approach on its head, =
delivering a single dose of ultrahigh-power radiation in a burst that typic=
ally lasts less than one-tenth of a second. In study after study, this tech=
nique causes significantly less injury to normal tissue than conventional r=
adiation does, without compromising its antitumor effect.</p><p>At CERN, wh=
ich I visited last July, the approach is being tested and refined on accele=
rators that were never intended for medicine. If ongoing experiments here a=
nd around the world continue to bear out results, FLASH could transform rad=
iotherapy=E2=80=94delivering stronger treatments, fewer side effects, and b=
roader access to lifesaving care.</p><p>=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s generating a =
lot of excitement,=E2=80=9D says Wuensch, a researcher at CERN=E2=80=99s Li=
near Electron Accelerator for Research (CLEAR) facility. =E2=80=9CWe accele=
rator people are thinking, Oh, wow, here=E2=80=99s an application of our te=
chnology that has a societal impact which is more immediate than most high-=
energy physics.=E2=80=9D</p><h2>The Unlikely Birth of FLASH Therapy</h2><p>=
The breakthrough that led to FLASH emerged from a line of experiments that =
began in the 1990s at <a href=3D"https://institut-curie.org/" target=3D"_bl=
ank">Institut Curie</a> in Orsay, near Paris. Researcher <a href=3D"https:/=
/institut-curie.org/person/vincent-favaudon" target=3D"_blank">Vincent Fava=
udon</a> was using a low-energy electron accelerator to study radiation che=
mistry. Targeting the accelerator at mouse lungs, Favaudon expected the rad=
iation to produce scar tissue, or fibrosis. But when he exposed the lungs t=
o ultrafast blasts of radiation, at doses a thousand times as high as what=
=E2=80=99s used in conventional radiation therapy, the expected fibrosis ne=
ver appeared.</p><p>Puzzled, Favaudon turned to <a href=3D"https://scholar.=
google.com/citations?user=3Dxx8VQkMAAAAJ&amp;hl=3Dfr" target=3D"_blank">Mar=
ie-Catherine Vozenin</a>, a radiation biologist at Curie who specialized in=
 radiation-induced fibrosis. =E2=80=9CWhen I looked at the slides, there wa=
s indeed no fibrosis, which was very, very surprising for this type of dose=
,=E2=80=9D recalls Vozenin, who now works at <a href=3D"https://www.hug.ch/=
en" target=3D"_blank">Geneva University Hospitals</a>, in Switzerland.</p><=
p></p><div class=3D"rebellt-item
        ieee-sidebar-left
       =20
       =20
        col1" id=3D"rebelltitem1" data-id=3D"1" data-reload-ads=3D"false" d=
ata-is-image=3D"False" data-href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/flash-radioth=
erapy/how-to-measure-radiation-doses" data-basename=3D"how-to-measure-radia=
tion-doses" data-post-id=3D"2675544839" data-published-at=3D"1772550501" da=
ta-use-pagination=3D"False">
        <h3 data-role=3D"headline">
           =20
                How to Measure Radiation Doses
           =20
           =20
        </h3>
        <p>Radiation therapy uses a variety of units to refer to the amount=
 of energy received by the patient. Here are the main ones under the Intern=
ational System of Units, or SI.</p><p><strong>Gray (Gy):</strong> A measure=
 of the absorbed dose=E2=80=94that is, how much radiation energy is absorbe=
d by the body. One gray equals 1 joule of radiation energy per kilogram of =
matter. FLASH delivers a single dose of 40 Gy or more in a fraction of a se=
cond. Conventional radiation therapy, by contrast, may deliver a total dose=
 of 40 to 80 Gy but over the course of several weeks.</p><p><strong>Sievert=
 (Sv):</strong> A measure of the effective dose=E2=80=94that is, the health=
 effects of the radiation, with different types of ionizing radiation (gamm=
a rays, X-rays, alpha particles, and so on) having different effects. One s=
ievert equals 1 joule per kilogram weighted for the biological effectivenes=
s of the radiation and the tissues exposed.</p>
</div>
<div class=3D"rebellt-item
       =20
       =20
       =20
        col1" id=3D"rebelltitem9" data-id=3D"9" data-reload-ads=3D"false" d=
ata-is-image=3D"False" data-href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/flash-radioth=
erapy/particle-9" data-basename=3D"particle-9" data-post-id=3D"2675544839" =
data-published-at=3D"1772551718" data-use-pagination=3D"False">
        <p>The pair expanded the experiments to include cancerous tumors. T=
he results upended a long-held trade-off of radiotherapy: the idea that you=
 can=E2=80=99t destroy a tumor without also damaging the host. =E2=80=9CThi=
s differential effect is really what we want in radiation oncology, not dam=
aging normal tissue but killing the tumors,=E2=80=9D Vozenin says.</p><p>Th=
ey repeated the protocol across different types of tissue and tumors. By 20=
14, they had gathered enough evidence to publish their findings in <a href=
=3D"https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/scitranslmed.3008973" target=3D"_bl=
ank"><em>Science Translational Medicine</em></a>. Their experiments confirm=
ed that delivering an ultrahigh dose of 10 gray or more in less than a tent=
h of a second could eradicate tumors in mice while leaving surrounding heal=
thy tissue virtually unharmed. For comparison, a typical chest X-ray delive=
rs about 0.1 milligray, while a session of conventional radiation therapy m=
ight deliver a total of about 2 gray per day. (The authors called the effec=
t =E2=80=9CFLASH=E2=80=9D because of the quick, high doses involved, but it=
=E2=80=99s not an acronym.)</p>
</div>
<div class=3D"rebellt-item
