three-sets-of-images-comparing-highly-magnified-tissue-samples.jpg?id=3D651=
11609&amp;width=3D980" width=3D"1654" height=3D"856" alt=3D"Three sets of i=
mages comparing highly magnified tissue samples.">
                <small class=3D"image-media media-caption"><p>Although many=
 cancer experts were skeptical about the FLASH effect on healthy tissue whe=
n it was first announced in 2014, numerous studies have since confirmed and=
 expanded on those results. In a 2020 paper, a lung tissue sample taken 4 m=
onths after being exposed to conventional radiotherapy [center] shows many =
more dark spots indicating scarring than a sample exposed to FLASH [right].=
 The nonirradiated sample [left] is the control.</p></small>
                <small class=3D"image-media media-photo-credit"><p><a href=
=3D"https://aacrjournals.org/clincancerres/article/26/6/1497/83297/FLASH-Ir=
radiation-Spares-Lung-Progenitor-Cells-and" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopen=
er noreferrer"><u>Vincent Favaudon/American Association for Cancer Research=
</u></a></p></small>
       =20
</div>
<div class=3D"rebellt-item
       =20
       =20
       =20
        col1" id=3D"rebelltitem3" data-id=3D"3" data-reload-ads=3D"false" d=
ata-is-image=3D"False" data-href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/flash-radioth=
erapy/particle-3" data-basename=3D"particle-3" data-post-id=3D"2675544839" =
data-published-at=3D"1772550501" data-use-pagination=3D"False">
        <p>Many cancer experts were skeptical. The FLASH effect seemed almo=
st too good to be true. =E2=80=9CIt didn=E2=80=99t get a lot of traction at=
 first,=E2=80=9D recalls <a href=3D"https://med.stanford.edu/profiles/Billy=
_Loo" target=3D"_blank">Billy Loo</a>, a Stanford radiation oncologist spec=
ializing in lung cancer. =E2=80=9CThey described a phenomenon that ran coun=
ter to decades of established radiobiology dogma.=E2=80=9D</p><p>But in the=
 years since then, researchers have observed the effect across a wide range=
 of tumor types and animals=E2=80=94beyond mice to zebra fish, fruit flies,=
 and even a few human subjects, with the same protective effect in the brai=
n, lungs, skin, muscle, heart, and bone.</p><p>Why this happens remains a m=
ystery. =E2=80=9CWe have investigated a lot of hypotheses, and all of them =
have been wrong,=E2=80=9D says Vozenin. Currently, the most plausible theor=
y emerging from her team=E2=80=99s research points to metabolism: Healthy a=
nd cancerous cells may process reactive oxygen species=E2=80=94unstable oxy=
gen-containing molecules generated during radiation=E2=80=94in very differe=
nt ways.</p><h2>Adapting Accelerators for FLASH</h2><p>At the time of the f=
irst FLASH publication, Loo and his team at Stanford were also focused on d=
ramatically speeding up radiation delivery. But Loo wasn=E2=80=99t chasing =
a radiobiological breakthrough. He was trying to solve a different problem:=
 motion.</p><p>=E2=80=9CThe tumors that we treat are always moving targets,=
=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s particularly true in the lung, w=
here because of breathing motion, the tumors are constantly moving.=E2=80=
=9D</p><p>To bring FLASH therapy out of the lab and into clinical use, rese=
archers like Vozenin and Loo needed machines capable of delivering fast, hi=
gh doses with pinpoint precision deep inside the body. Most early studies r=
elied on low-energy electron beams like Favaudon=E2=80=99s 4.5-megaelectron=
-volt Kinetron=E2=80=94sufficient for surface tumors, but unable to reach m=
ore than a few centimeters into a human body. Treating deep-seated cancers =
in the lung, brain, or abdomen would require far higher particle energies.<=
/p>
</div>
