/photo-of-floor-to-ceiling-electromagnetic-hardware-with-many-tubes-and-pip=
es-some-of-which-is-copper-colored.jpg?id=3D65111435&amp;width=3D980" width=
=3D"2000" height=3D"1341" alt=3D"Photo of floor-to-ceiling electromagnetic =
hardware with many tubes and pipes, some of which is copper-colored.">
                <small class=3D"image-media media-caption"><p>At CERN, rese=
archers working on FLASH are developing this hardware to boost electrons to=
 ultrahigh power within a short distance. </p></small>
                <small class=3D"image-media media-photo-credit"><p>CERN</p>=
</small>
       =20
</div>
<div class=3D"rebellt-item
       =20
       =20
       =20
        col1" id=3D"rebelltitem5" data-id=3D"5" data-reload-ads=3D"false" d=
ata-is-image=3D"False" data-href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/flash-radioth=
erapy/particle-5" data-basename=3D"particle-5" data-post-id=3D"2675544839" =
data-published-at=3D"1772550501" data-use-pagination=3D"False">
        <p>They also needed an alternative to conventional X-rays. In a cli=
nical linac, X-ray photons are produced by dumping high-energy electrons in=
to a bremsstrahlung target, which is made of a material with a high atomic =
number, like tungsten or copper. The target slows the electrons, converting=
 their kinetic energy into X-ray photons. It=E2=80=99s an inherently ineffi=
cient process that wastes most of the beam power as heat and makes it extre=
mely difficult to reach the ultrahigh dose rates required for FLASH. High-e=
nergy electrons, by contrast, can be switched on and off within millisecond=
s. And because they have a charge and can be steered by magnets, electrons =
can be precisely guided to reach tumors deep within the body. (Researchers =
are also investigating protons and carbon ions; see the sidebar, =E2=80=9CW=
hat=E2=80=99s the Best Particle for FLASH Therapy?=E2=80=9D)</p><p>Loo turn=
ed to the <a href=3D"https://www6.slac.stanford.edu/" target=3D"_blank">SLA=
C National Accelerator Laboratory</a> in Menlo Park, Calif., where physicis=
t <a href=3D"https://profiles.stanford.edu/sami-tantawi" target=3D"_blank" =
rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Sami Gamal-Eldin Tantawi</a> was redefining how=
 electromagnetic waves move through linear accelerators. Tantawi=E2=80=99s =
findings allowed scientists to precisely control how energy is delivered to=
 particles=E2=80=94paving the way for compact, efficient, and finely tunabl=
e machines. It was exactly the kind of technology FLASH therapy would need =
to target tumors deep inside the body.</p><p>Meanwhile, Vozenin and other E=
uropean researchers turned to CERN, best known for its 27-kilometer Large H=
adron Collider (LHC) and the 2012 discovery of the Higgs boson, the =E2=80=
=9CGod particle=E2=80=9D that gives other particles their mass. </p><p clas=
s=3D"ieee-inbody-related">RELATED: <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/par=
ticle-physics-ai" target=3D"_blank">AI Hunts for the Next Big Thing in Phys=
ics</a></p><p>CERN is also home to a range of smaller linear accelerators=
=E2=80=94including CLEAR, where Wuensch and his team are adapting high-ener=
gy physics tools for medicine.</p>
</div>
<div class=3D"rebellt-item
        ieee-sidebar-left
       =20
