d services</a>. This is despite the fact that the 2018 U.S. <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CLOUD_Act" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"=
_blank">CLOUD Act</a> allows U.S. federal <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.=
org/tag/law-enforcement">law enforcement</a> =E2=80=93 at least in theory =
=E2=80=93 to compel U.S.-based firms to hand over data that=E2=80=99s store=
d abroad. </p><h2>Who do you trust?</h2><p>But those hypothetical risks to =
digital services have become more real as transatlantic relations have sour=
ed under the second Trump administration. The U.S. has <a href=3D"https://w=
ww.cbc.ca/news/politics/greenland-us-trump-canada-governor-general-mary-sim=
on-9.7119074" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">openly threaten=
ed</a> to invade an EU member state and <a href=3D"https://euobserver.com/1=
9745/eu-rejects-us-claims-of-censorship-over-tech-rules-after-visa-bans/" r=
el=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">sanctioned</a> a European Comm=
issioner for passing <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/legislation">=
legislation</a> the <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/white-house">W=
hite House</a> dislikes. </p><p>After the White House sanctioned the Nether=
lands-based International Criminal Court in February 2025, Court staffers <=
a href=3D"https://apnews.com/article/icc-trump-sanctions-karim-khan-court-a=
4b4c02751ab84c09718b1b95cbd5db3" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_bla=
nk">claimed</a> Microsoft locked the Court=E2=80=99s chief prosecutor out o=
f his email (Microsoft<a href=3D"https://www.politico.eu/article/microsoft-=
did-not-cut-services-international-criminal-court-president-american-sancti=
ons-trump-tech-icc-amazon-google/" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_b=
lank"> has denied this</a>). Around the same time, the U.S. <a href=3D"http=
s://kyivindependent.com/us-threatens-to-shut-off-starlink-if-ukraine-wont-s=
ign-minerals-deal-sources-tell-reuters/" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=
=3D"_blank">reportedly threatened</a> to sever EU ally Ukraine=E2=80=99s ac=
cess to crucial <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/starlink">Starlink=
</a> <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/satellite-internet">satellite=
 internet</a> as leverage during trade negotiations.</p><p></p><div class=
=3D"rblad-ieee_in_content"></div><p></p><p>=E2=80=9CThe geopolitical risk i=
sn=E2=80=99t just the most extreme form of a doomsday =E2=80=98kill switch=
=E2=80=99 where Washington turns off Europe=E2=80=99s internet,=E2=80=9D <a=
 href=3D"https://fermigier.com/" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_bla=
nk">St=C3=A9fane Fermigier</a> of <a href=3D"https://euro-stack.com/pages/a=
bout" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">EuroStack</a>, an indus=
try group that supports European digital independence. =E2=80=9CIt is the s=
elective degradation of services and a total lack of retaliatory leverage.=
=E2=80=9D</p><p>What, then, is the EU to do? <a href=3D"https://blog.datace=
nter-paris.com/2026/01/24/liste-des-datacenters-secnumcloud-en-france-heber=
gement-souverain-pour-donnees-sensibles/" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" targe=
t=3D"_blank">France</a> offers an example. Even before 2025, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/france">France</a> implemented <a href=3D"https:=
//www.spscommerce.com/eur/blog/what-is-secnumcloud-and-does-my-company-need=
-to-qualify/" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">harsh restricti=
ons</a> on non-EU cloud providers in public services =E2=80=93 providers mu=
st locate data in the EU, rely on EU-based staff, and may not have majority=
-non-EU shareholders. Now, EU policymakers are following France=E2=80=99s l=
ead.</p><p>In October 2025, the EC issued a two-part <a href=3D"https://com=
mission.europa.eu/document/09579818-64a6-4dd5-9577-446ab6219113_en" rel=3D"=
noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">framework</a> for judging cloud prov=
iders bidding for public sector contracts. In the first part, the framework=
 lays out a sort of sovereignty ladder. The more that a provider is subject=
 to EU law, the higher its sovereignty level on this ladder. Any prospectiv=
e bidder must first meet a certain level, depending on the tender.</p><p>Qu=
alifying bidders then move to the second part, where their =E2=80=9Csoverei=
gnty=E2=80=9D is scored in more detail. Using too much proprietary software=
; over-relying on supply chains from outside the EU; having non-EU support =
staff; <a href=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/liability">liability</a> to=
 non-EU laws like the CLOUD Act: all hurt a bidder=E2=80=99s score. </p><p>=
The framework was created for <a href=3D"https://commission.europa.eu/news-=
and-media/news/commission-moves-forward-cloud-sovereignty-eur-180-million-t=
ender-2025-10-10_en" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">one tend=
er</a>, but observers say it sets a major precedent. Cloud providers biddin=
g for state contracts across Europe may need to follow it, and it may influ=
ence legislation on both national and EU-wide levels.</p><h2>A question of =
scale</h2><p>Who, then, will receive high marks? At the moment, the answer =
is not simple. The EU cloud scene is quite fragmented. Numerous modest EU p=
roviders offer =E2=80=9Csovereign cloud=E2=80=9D services =E2=80=93 such as=
 Scaleway, OVHcloud, and Deutsche Telekom=E2=80=99s T-Systems =E2=80=93 but=
 <a href=3D"https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/poi3.358" rel=
=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">none are on the scale</a> of AWS=
 or Google Cloud.</p><p>Inertia is on the side of the U.S. cloud giants, wh=
o can invest in their infrastructure and services on a far grander scale th=
an their European counterparts. Some U.S. providers <a href=3D"https://aws.=
amazon.com/blogs/security/aws-european-sovereign-cloud-achieves-first-compl=
iance-milestone-soc-2-and-c5-reports-plus-seven-iso-certifications/" rel=3D=
"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">now offer</a> cloud services they s=
ay comply with the Commission=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ccloud sovereignty=E2=80=9D=
 demands.</p><p>Some European observers, like EuroStack, <a href=3D"https:/=
/euro-stack.com/blog/2025/10/cloud-sovereignty-framework-comparison" rel=3D=
"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">say</a> such promises are hollow so=
 long as a provider=E2=80=99s parent company is subject to the likes of the=
 CLOUD Act, and loopholes in the Commission=E2=80=99s process remain open. =
An AWS spokesperson told <em>Spectrum</em> it had not disclosed any non-US =
enterprise or government data to the U.S. government under the CLOUD Act; a=
 Google spokesperson said that its most sensitive EU offerings =E2=80=9Care=
 subject to local laws, not US law=E2=80=9D.</p><p>Even if a project like E=
URO-3C can offer a large-scale alternative, the US cloud giants have anothe=
r sort of inertia. Many developers =E2=80=93 and many public purchasers of =
their services =E2=80=93 will need convincing to leave behind a familiar en=
vironment.</p><p></p><div class=3D"rblad-ieee_in_content"></div><p></p><p>=
=E2=80=9CIf you look at AWS, you look at Google, they=E2=80=99ve created so=
me super technology. It=E2=80=99s very convenient, it=E2=80=99s easy to use=
,=E2=80=9D says <a href=3D"https://nl.linkedin.com/in/arnoldjuffer" rel=3D"=
noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">Arnold Juffer</a>, CEO of the Nether=
lands-based cloud provider <a href=3D"https://nebul.com/" rel=3D"noopener n=
oreferrer" target=3D"_blank">Nebul</a>. =E2=80=9COnce you=E2=80=99re in tha=
t platform, in that ecosystem, it=E2=80=99s very hard to get out.=E2=80=9D<=
/p><p><a href=3D"https://bisi.org.uk/martyna-chmura" rel=3D"noopener norefe=
rrer" target=3D"_blank">Martyna Chmura</a>, an analyst at the Bloomsbury In=
telligence and Security Institute, a London-based think tank, sees some EU =
developers taking a mixed approach. =E2=80=9CMany organizations are already=
 moving toward multi-cloud setups, using European or sovereign providers fo=
r sensitive workloads while still relying on hyperscalers for certain servi=
ces,=E2=80=9D she says.</p><p>In that case, the EU=E2=80=99s top-down deman=
ds may encourage developers to use EU providers for sensitive applications =
=E2=80=93 like government services, transport, <a href=3D"https://spectrum.=
ieee.org/tag/autonomous-vehicles">autonomous vehicles</a>, and some <a href=
=3D"https://spectrum.ieee.org/tag/industrial-automation">industrial automat=
ion</a> =E2=80=93 even if it=E2=80=99s inconvenient in the short term, or i=
f it causes even more fragmentation of the EU cloud scene. =E2=80=9CRunning=
 systems across different platforms can increase integration costs and make=
 security and data governance more complicated. In some cases, organisation=
s could lose some of the efficiency and cost advantages that come from usin=
g large hyperscale platforms,=E2=80=9D Chmura says.</p><p>=E2=80=9COverall,=
 the EU appears willing to accept some of these trade-offs,=E2=80=9D Chmura=
 says.</p><div class=3D"around-the-web"><div class=3D"from-your-site__headl=
